I couldn't agree with you more. My uncle was a Korean WAR vet and it took about twelve years for it to kill him. All he has is a plaque on the ground where he was buried to show for it.<br><br>
In my home town, money was appropriated for a Vietnam Memorial on a state level. The veterans decided to include the Korean WAR casualties along with the Vietnam war names. It was the only just decision to make. <br><br>
When you stated that you were involved in the Korean &quot;thing&quot;, it so much reminded me of when veteran organizations would not recognize Vietnam as a war, either, thus refused our membership.
